Lachanius seems to have won the respect and love of those under his control, and the people of Pisa erected in his honour in their Forum a statue with an inscription expressed in such terms of eulogy and regard as to move Rutilius to tears when he read it on his visit to Pisa. Nor was it at Pisa alone, but also throughout Tuscany‚ that Rutilius found tokens of the veneration in which his father was held}

From the words of Rutilius' affectionate tribute to his father‚² it may be gathered that the latter, besides being consularis Tusciae,³ had a-lso held the offices of comes sacrarum Zarqitz'onum of the Empire of the west, of quaestor* and of praefectus urbis.
